panish Catholic Journals in the Early Twentieth Century / rNavarro, Jaume -- tPart IV. Mediating Tradition -- tThe Analogy of Marshall McLuhan / rMorrissey, Christopher S. -- tVetera Novis Augere: Neo-Scholastic Philosophers and Their Concepts of Tradition / rPaul, Herman -- tThomas Aquinas or John Henry Newman? The Intellectual Itinerary of Johannes Willebrands / rSchelkens, Karim -- tAbout the Authors -- tIndex of Persons  aIn So What's New about Scholasticism? thirteen international scholars gauge the extraordinary impact of a religiously inspired conceptual framework in a modern society. The essays that are brought together in this volume reveal that Neo-Thomism became part of contingent social contexts and varying intellectual domains. Rather than an ecclesiastic project of like-minded believers, Neo-Thomism was put into place as a source of inspiration for various concepts of modernization and progress. This volume reconstructs how Neo-Thomism sought to resolve disparities, annul contradictions and reconcile incongruent, new developments. It asks the question why Neo-Thomist ideas and arguments were put into play and how they were transferred across various scientific disciplines and artistic media, growing into one of the most influential master-narratives of the twentieth century. Edward Baring, Dries Bosschaert, James Chappel, Adi Efal-Lautenschläger, Rajesh Heynickx, Sigrid Leyssen, Christopher Morrissey, Annette Mülberger, Jaume Navarro, Herman Paul, Karim Schelkens, Wim Weymans and John Carter Wood reconstruct a bewildering, yet decipherable thought-structure that has left a deep mark on twentieth century politics, philosophy, science and religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Jul 2018) 4aNeo-Scholasticism. 4aNeuscholastik. 4aNew Theology. 4aNouvelle Théologie. 4aThomas Aquinas. 4aThomas von Aqu